# Overview
Creates a root level `just latest-versions` command which scans git tags, then returns the stable and latest tag for each component. 

Current output:
```
{
   ...
  "op-challenger": {
    "stable": "v1.5.2",
    "latest": "v1.5.3-rc.3"
  },
  "op-conductor": {
    "stable": "v0.7.3",
    "latest": "v0.7.3"
  },
  "op-contracts": {
    "stable": "v4.0.0",
    "latest": "v4.1.0-rc.2"
  },
  "op-deployer": {
    "stable": "v0.4.2",
    "latest": "v0.4.2"
  },
  ...
}
```

# Questions
1. How should we handle op-deployer/op-contracts since users don't always want the latest for those? Should we print out a nested structure like this as part of the output or does that create more confusion?
```
   {
     "op-node": "v1.15.1"
     "op-contracts": {
       "v2": {"op-contracts": "v2.1.0", "op-deployer": "v0.2.3"},
       "v3":  {"op-contracts": "v3.1.0", "op-deployer": "v0.3.5"},
       "v4": {"op-contracts": "v4.0.0", "op-deployer": "v0.4.2"}
     }
   }
```
2. By default should we only output releases, or print -rc as shown in output above? We could have an input arg to the recipe to specify only "releases" vs "all"
3. Should we include `op-geth` or any other components whose source code is not in the monorepo?

# Related Issues
* Closes https://github.com/ethereum-optimism/optimism/issues/17396
